{"id":"1710.03707","submitter":"David Cohen","authors":"David Bruce Cohen","title":"Lamplighters admit weakly aperiodic SFTs","comments":"10 pages, 3 figures have been added, some corrections have been made","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.GR math.DS","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Let $A$ be a finite set and $G$ a group. A closed subset $X$ of $A^G$ is\ncalled a subshift if the action of $G$ on $A^G$ preserves $X$. If $K$ is a\nclosed subset of $A^G$ such that membership in $K$ is determined by looking at\na fixed finite set of coordinates, and $X$ is the intersection of all\ntranslates of $K$ under the action of $G$, then $X$ is called a subshift of\nfinite type (SFT). If an SFT is nonempty and contains no finite $G$-orbits, it\nis said to be weakly aperiodic. A virtually cyclic group has no weakly\naperiodic SFT, and Carroll and Penland have conjectured that a group with no\nweakly aperiodic SFT must be virtually cyclic. Answering a question of Jeandel,\nwe show that lamplighters always admit weakly aperiodic SFTs.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 10 Oct 2017 16:26:35 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 2 Feb 2018 06:31:05 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-02-05"}
